article.headline: After court appearance, Clemons rules the court
article.linkText: Clemons puts distractions aside to lead No. 22 Missouri
article.story: COLUMBIA, Mo. (AP) -- Ricky Clemons didn't let his off-court problems bother him against Nebraska, hitting six of his first eight shots and scoring 20 points in Missouri's 67-50 victory Tuesday night. About four hours before game time, the junior guard pleaded not guilty at a brief hearing to a felony charge of choking a woman and refusing to let her leave his apartment. A trial date will be set March 3 in Boone County Circuit Court. Clemons led Missouri (16-6, 7-4 Big 12; No. 22 ESPN/USA Today) to a season-best 13 3-pointers in 36 attempts against a sagging defense, going 6-for-12 from long range, and he added three steals. Freshman Jimmy McKinney flirted with a triple-double, getting nine points, eight rebounds and eight assists for Missouri, 13-0 in the Hearnes Center for the first time since 1995-96. Rickey Paulding had 11 points to become the second Missouri player to top 1,000 career points this season, joining center Arthur Johnson, who had 10 points. Missouri's previous high for 3-pointers this season was 11 against Wisconsin-Green Bay and Colorado. The Tigers finished seven shy of the school record for 3-pointers made and one shy of attempts, both last season at Colorado. Missouri attempted 29 shots inside the 3-point arc, making 12 of them. The emphasis on 3-pointers left the Tigers without a free throw attempt until Travon Bryant drew a shooting foul with 7:32 left, making one of two. Missouri finished 4-for-7 from the line. Nate Johnson had 17 points and Andrew Drevo added 14 points and seven rebounds for Nebraska (9-15, 1-10), the Big 12's last-place team and winless at Missouri since 1995. The Cornhuskers have lost eight in a row and are 1-9 since Jake Muhleisen broke his hip Jan. 11. Missouri was 4-for-23 from 3-point range in a 63-56 victory at Nebraska on Jan. 29, including 1-for-10 misfiring by Clemons. Nebraska led 9-0 and 17-4 early in that game before collapsing in the second half. Clemons had 14 of the Tigers' first 23 points in the rematch. Missouri was 9-for-22 from 3-point range in the half, taking advantage of a defense apparently designed to control the 6-foot-9, 260-pound Johnson. Johnson was held to six points and one rebound in the half as the Tigers took a 37-28 lead.
